<HEADLINE>
FT  28 JUL 92 / International Company News: Canadian airlines again consider
merger
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GIBBENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CANADA'S two major airlines are resuming merger talks with federal
government approval.
Both Air Canada, privatised two years ago, and Canadian Airlines
International, owned by PWA Corporation of Calgary, took heavy losses in the
first half this year, and both are staggering under big debt loads.
They broke off merger talks late last year with acrimony, each saying it
would do better linking up with American carriers to achieve greater access
to the US market.
However, PWA says its lengthy talks with AMR, parent of American Airlines
for an alliance have been terminated. British Airways' acquisition of 21 per
cent of USAir for USDollars 750m last week effectively ended Air Canada's
flirtation with the American carrier.
Last night Air Canada chairman, Mr Claude Taylor, said: 'Powerful market
forces compel carriers to consider all their options and the existing
structure of the Canadian airline industry is not viable.'
He said the merger talks with PWA would resume this week, and Ottawa 'will
be monitoring them closely'.
A merger between the two could pose a dilemma for the government since it
would create a monopoly on Canadian routes and raise anti-trust concerns.
Air Canada reiterated its position that the existing structure of the
Canadian airline industry was not viable, and that 'survival is at stake'.
PWA also said last night that it has asked for and received the resignations
of all directors of wholly-owned subsidiary companies. The directors will
remain on the board of the parent company, PWA Corporation.
PWA said the reorganisation was to address directors' liability concerns.
</TEXT>
